questions.explanation:
Ben Green is a web developer with over 15 years experience, having worked in startups and agencies in California as well as many open source projects. In 2021, after being shocked by the immense power of Defi applications, he has committed his efforts toward understanding Ethereum and all of its related projects.

Luca Donnoh and Bartek are researchers from Italy and Poland (respectively) working at L2 Beat to provide important safety information to the community. Their efforts have made them the trusted source for the most salient details for users of the Ethereum ecosystem. We our merging our efforts between their ZK Catalog and Circuitscan to provide circuit verifier safety information.

questions.query: Project GitHub Repo
Have you participated in a previous Gitcoin Grants Round? If so, please name the rounds or link the builder profile associated with previous rounds.
Provide a brief overview of your tool, library, or framework. What specific problem or inefficiency in the development process does it address?
questions.explanation:
ZK circuits generate a Solidity contract to verify proofs but these contracts hide the circuit source and compilation details as a series of numbers. Circuitscan provides the next layer of visibility needed to trust ZK circuit verifiers on chain like any other smart contract verified on a block explorer.

ZK app developers can submit their Circom/Noir sources for compilation through the CLI application to verify their deployed verifier contracts.

ZK app users can generate proofs to interact with the applications using a block explorer, as well as analyze the source code for any issues.

questions.query: How does your project reduce development barriers, improve efficiency, or enhance the security of Web3 projects? Please provide specific examples or metrics if available.
questions.explanation:
Circuitscan reduces development barriers by making it easy for developers to compile large circuits on cloud machines with up to 512 GB of ram.

Circuitscan enhances the security of on-chain ZK dApps by providing the specific details necessary to check that a verifier contract doesn't contain any hidden backdoors by linking to the source file match on Github at the correct commit, and on Groth16 verifiers it prominently displays whether the second phase setup was done using P0tion to ensure that the contributions were not faked.

questions.query: Describe the current usage and support for your tool within the developer community. This could include GitHub stars, downloads, or testimonials from developers.

Starred on github by PSE developers ctrlc03. Followed on github by PSE developers divide-by-0 and glamperd.

How does your project contribute significantly to the Ethereum network's infrastructure? Please provide specific examples and metrics if available.
questions.explanation:
Circuit verifier Solidity contracts verified on Etherscan are opaque to the viewer. There's no way to quickly check that they match the source code on Github. When users can see this match, they can be sure that there's no backdoors inserted clandestinely.

Verified contracts on etherscan also come into play when a dapp's frontend becomes unusable. For a zk app with a missing frontend, Circuitscan provides a tool for generating proofs so that users never have to worry about being locked out.

questions.query: Describe any pioneering development work in your project, particularly in enhancing privacy, interoperability, or user experience.
questions.explanation:
Along the way of development of Circuitscan, I've made various improvements to the PSE P0seidon project frontend.

Circuitscan uses a WASM-compiled version of Trail of Bits' Circomspect for in-browser static analysis of Circom sources.

questions.query: What specific problems or challenges in the Ethereum ecosystem does your project address? How does your solution improve upon existing alternatives?
questions.explanation: Circuitscan is a circuit verifier explorer. Like verified contracts, a verified circuit verifier allows users to interact with applications directly if the frontend becomes unusable as well as ensures that the deployed source code matches the expected source code. Developers use a CLI to submit their circom sources to the verification server just like how Hardhat and Foundry submit deployed contracts to Etherscan. The frontend catalogs all verified submissions with source code and proving keys available for usage.

questions.query: Outline your project's roadmap and how the grant funds will be used to achieve your development goals.
questions.explanation:
Funds will be used to:

* Refactor the CLI internally so that it can be easily integrated with Circomkit
* Update the Groth16 multi-verifier to match the updated Semaphore v4 deployment

questions.query: How does your project contribute to the decentralization and security of the Ethereum network?
questions.explanation: Rug pulls, scams, and hacks plague blockchain users. By developing strong tooling around the applications, we can mitigate these risks and increase confidence in the ecosystem.
